LEGIONNAIRE'S DISEASE EPIDEMIOLOGY (4)
======================================
[This posting and "Legionnaire's disease epidemiology (5)"
collect several replies, through Sat, 6 Jan, in response to the
query on how to differentiate community acquired and nosocomial
legionellosis:]

[1]
From: "LOUIS POLISH" <LPOLISH@umms001.ab.umd.edu>
Organization: University of Md Medical System
Date: Fri, 5 Jan 1996 16:22:46 EDT
In response to the Legionnaire's Epidemiology:RFI and the followup
Legionnaire's Epidemiology (2) concerning the distinction between
community and nosocomially acquired infections - I agree that the data as
presented give no indication that either patient was infected with
Legionella. However, a nosocomial infection is one in
which there is no evidence that the infection was present or
incubating at the time of admission. The definition is therefore
dependent on a knowledge of the incubation period of the particular
infectious disease under discussion but as Dr. Wallis points out, in
general, the patient must be in the hospital at least 48 hours.
Since the incubation period of Legionnaire's disease is approximately
2-10 days, the fact that the patient was in the hospital 2 days
or longer would not automatically define this as a nosocomial
infection. Knowledge of the incubation period, risk factors for
infection, exposures etc. would need to be considered to decide
whether the infection was aquired in the community or in the hospital.
--
Louis Polish MD
Hospital Epidemiologist
Univ. of Maryland Medical System
410-328-5757
e-mail: lpolish@umms001.ab.umd.edu
