[2]
From: Drbob6@aol.com (Bob Sharbaugh)
Date: Fri, 5 Jan 1996 14:44:09 -0500
In response to the request for information concerning the differentiation
between nosocomial and community acquired Legionnaire's disease:
The traditional definition of "nosocomial" infection of any kind, simply
stated, would include any infection which manifests itself greater than 48
hours after admission and yet was not incubating at the time of admission.
In this particular case, one must also take into account the incubation
period for Legionellosis which is generally 5-6 days.
It is of interest that, apparantly, in neither of the cases which you present
was the cause of death ascribed to Legionellosis. However, if we assume that
Legionellosis was, indeeed, the cause of death, then, according to the above
generalized definition of "nosocomial", neither of the cases would be
considered as "nosocomial" or hospital associated.
--
Bob Sharbaugh, Ph.D.
Consulting epidemiologist
Charleston, SC
e-mail: Drbob6@aol.com
