[3]
From: Carol Metcalf <cmetcalf@u.washington.edu>
Date: Fri, 5 Jan 1996 11:58:49 -0800 (PST)

Joseph Wagner posed the question "Would anyone be able to tell me how
community acquired Legionnaire's is differentiated from nosocomial?"
The following reference may be of interest:
Strebel PM et al. Legionnaires' disease in a Johannesburg teaching
hospital. Investigation and control of an outbreak. South African Medical
Journal 1988; 73(6) 329-33.
This reports on an outbreak investigation of a time cluster of 12 cases in a
hospital in which some cases were community-acquired, some were
nosocomially-acquired, and in some cases it was not initially clear where
the infection had been acquired. The investigators used epidemiologic
reasoning to distinguish between nosocomial and community cases. The
nosocomial cases were associated with being on a ventillator, but not
with the water supply despite the finding of culture-positive water sites.
--
Carol Metcalf
University of Washington, Seattle, WA, USA
e-mail: cmetcalf@u.washington.edu
